article.description:
Kara Lawson scored 16 points and Erin
Buescher added 14 to help the Sacramento Monarchs rally for a 76-74
victory over the Seattle Storm on Saturday.
article.headline: Lawson, Buescher fuel Monarchs' comeback win
article.linkText: Buescher fuels Monarchs' comeback win vs. Storm
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Erin Buescher made two big baskets in
a 19-second span in the fourth quarter for the Sacramento Monarchs.

But the modest Buescher sidestepped much of the credit, saying
her teammates made the difference on both baskets in the Monarchs'
76-74 victory over the Seattle Storm on Saturday.

Kara Lawson had 16 points and Buescher finished with 14 for the
Monarchs in the comeback victory. The Monarchs took their first
lead in the fourth quarter when Buescher scored off her own miss
for a 71-70 advantage with 2:47 remaining.

"The shot clock was running down and that (perimeter) shot is
not usually one I take," said Buescher, whose banker from close
range put the Monarchs ahead for good. "Yo (Yolanda Griffith) and
Nicole (Powell) held their defenders off and the ball was just
there for me. I made the shot, but it was all them."

Seconds later, after a Seattle turnover, Buescher sprinted up
court and converted a layup off a pass from Ticha Penicheiro for a
73-70 with 2:29 remaining.

"Ticha and I made eye contact. She knows I love to run the
court and she made a perfect pass," said Buescher, a reserve post
player enjoying her best season in the WNBA.

Betty Lennox scored a season-high 23 points for Seattle (6-6),
which had its modest two-game winning streak snapped. Lauren
Jackson added 17 points and nine rebounds, and Barbara Turner had
14 points.

The Monarchs controlled Seattle perennial All-Star point guard
Sue Bird, who had five points, four assists and six of the Storms
25 turnovers.

"She (Bird) is big. She's the John Stockton of our league,"
Sacramento coach John Whisenant said. "To a certain degree
containing her helps us contain Lauren (Jackson). We try to wear
(Bird) down so she is tired in the fourth quarter."

Bird missed a 3-point attempt in the closing seconds that would
have tied the game. She gave credit to the Sacramento defense for
part of Seattle's offensive troubles in the fourth quarter when it
made 2-of-12 field goal attempts.

"A lot of times we got caught standing around in the fourth
quarter," Bird said. "It felt like we were standing around and
watching. Part of that is what they do defensively, they really
make you work."

Despite the problems, the Storm still had a chance to win at the
end. Fouled on a 3-point attempt, Turner made all three attempts,
pulling Seattle to 75-73 with 24.2 seconds left.

Following a free throw by the Monarchs' Nicole Powell, Turner
made one of two free throws with 1.2 seconds left.

After shooting well through three quarters, the Storm went cold
in the fourth. They went the final 7:53 without a field goal,
although they did convert 14 straight free throws before Turner's
miss.

"They are a physical team and they picked up their defense at
the end and that's what helped create our turnovers," Lennox said.
"We let this game slip away."

Ticha Penicheiro had 12 points for the Monarchs (5-4), who had
lost three of their previous four games.

The Storm were embarrassed three weeks earlier at Arco Arena,
losing 87-66.
